      <p>Brisbane has a long, consistent history with severe weather. The November 2014 hailstorm, the October 2020 Halloween hail event, the December 2023 supercell across the south-east, and the regular procession of summer storms through the suburbs all leave behind a familiar pattern: damaged tile and Colorbond roofs, dented metal roller doors, broken skylights and windows, fallen tree limbs, and water ingress through compromised flashings. Most of these claims are settled in a normal cadence within three to nine months. But for sellers, life does not always wait for an insurance assessor's diary to clear. People separate, downsize, relocate for work, or simply decide that this is the year to move, and the campaign cannot always be paused while a roof replacement makes its way through the queue.</p>

      <p>This article is for Brisbane owners who are preparing to sell, or are already on the market, with an open insurance claim or unfinished storm-related repair. It walks through the disclosure obligations, the contract mechanics under the Queensland standard contract, the buyer-confidence considerations, and the practical sequencing decisions that determine whether the claim becomes a small footnote in the campaign or a deal-breaker.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The three positions sellers find themselves in</h2>
      <p>Almost every storm-damage sale falls into one of three positions, and the right strategy depends on which one applies.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Position one: damage assessed, claim accepted, repairs scheduled or in progress.</strong> The insurer has confirmed coverage, a scope of works exists, and a builder or roofer is engaged. The seller knows what is being repaired, when, and to what standard. This is the cleanest position to sell from: buyers can be shown the scope, the timeline, and the warranty, and the contract can be written around either completing repairs before settlement or assigning insurance proceeds at settlement.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Position two: damage assessed, claim under negotiation or partially disputed.</strong> The insurer has acknowledged the claim but the scope, sums insured, or cash settlement amount is still being discussed. Sellers often sit in this position for weeks or months, especially for hail roof claims where insurers and assessors disagree on whether the roof needs full replacement or partial restoration. This position is workable but requires careful disclosure and contract drafting.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Position three: damage exists, claim not yet lodged or fully assessed.</strong> The seller has not yet pursued a claim, or has lodged but is waiting for an initial assessor visit. This is the riskiest position to launch a campaign from, because the size and resolution of the claim are unknown. In most cases, the right move is to lodge or progress the claim before listing, so the campaign launches with at least an assessor's report in hand.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What you must disclose</h2>
      <p>Queensland's seller disclosure regime, including the Property Law Act 2023 disclosure requirements that have been in force since August 2025, requires sellers to give a Form 2 disclosure statement before contract. Storm and hail damage that has been repaired is generally not a separately disclosable item, provided the repairs were lawful and properly completed. Damage that is current or unrepaired, however, sits inside the broader common-law and statutory obligations not to mislead, and a buyer's solicitor will routinely ask the question directly.</p>

      <p>Practical disclosure for storm damage looks like this. Provide the date and nature of the event. Provide the insurance assessor's report or scope of works if you have one. Confirm the claim status (open, settled cash, repairs in progress, or completed). Provide a roofer's or builder's certificate or invoice for completed repairs. For tile roofs, provide evidence of tile replacement and bedding repointing where applicable. For Colorbond roofs replaced under claim, provide the new roof warranty and, where the work was building-approval territory (rare for a like-for-like roof swap, but possible for structural repairs), the certificate of completion.</p>

      <p>Do not assume buyers will not ask. They will. A buyer's building and pest inspector will look at the roof, identify the work, and write a report that the buyer's solicitor will use to ask follow-up questions. Disclosure that pre-empts these questions builds confidence; disclosure that drags out under inspection report pressure damages it.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How the Queensland standard contract handles unrepaired damage</h2>
      <p>The Queensland standard residential contract places the risk of damage between contract date and settlement on the seller. The seller must give the property at settlement in substantially the same condition as at contract date, fair wear and tear excepted. For sales involving an open insurance claim, this principle is critical, because it determines what happens if more damage occurs (a second storm, for example) during the contract window.</p>

      <p>For a campaign launched while damage already exists, there are three contract approaches that work in practice.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Repair before settlement.</strong> The seller commits in the contract to complete the agreed scope of works before settlement, with a holdback or special condition tying part of settlement funds to satisfactory completion. This is cleanest for buyers but commits the seller to delivering tradespeople on a fixed timeline. In a wet season or post-storm Brisbane market with a backlog of roofing work, this can be hard to guarantee.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Assignment of insurance proceeds at settlement.</strong> The seller assigns the right to insurance proceeds (or cash settles the claim with the insurer pre-settlement and reduces the contract price by an agreed allowance). The buyer takes on the property and the repair project. Some buyers will accept this in exchange for a price reduction; many will not, because they prefer the certainty of buying a finished property. This works best where the buyer is a builder, developer, or experienced renovator.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Price-adjusted as-is sale.</strong> The seller discloses the damage, prices the property accordingly, and contracts on an as-is basis with a clear special condition that the buyer accepts the damage and waives any later claim against the seller. This is the simplest legal structure but it requires a sophisticated buyer and a price that genuinely reflects the repair cost plus a buffer for buyer risk.</p>

      <p>Whichever approach is used, the seller's solicitor must draft the special conditions tightly. Generic boilerplate is not enough. The scope of damage, the sums involved, the contractor identity, the timing, and the assignment mechanics all need to be specified.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Buyer confidence: the conversation that matters</h2>
      <p>Most buyers are not alarmed by storm damage in itself. Brisbane buyers know storms happen, and a property that has been through a major event and come out repaired and certified is often viewed positively (the new roof effectively resets the lifecycle clock on a major component). What alarms buyers is uncertainty: an open claim with unclear scope, a roof partially repaired with no documentation, an insurance file the seller cannot produce on request.</p>

      <p>The buyer-confidence playbook is straightforward. Lead with documentation. Have the assessor's report, the scope of works, the contractor's quote or invoice, and any warranties available in the contract pack. If repairs are complete, have a clear before-and-after story: dates, scope, cost, certifying tradesperson. If repairs are in progress, have the schedule and the contractor contact details. If repairs are deferred to the buyer, have the funds path mapped (insurer cash settlement amount, special condition mechanics, holdback if any).</p>

      <p>Buyers who walk away from storm-damaged sales almost always do so because the seller could not answer a basic question on the spot. The question is rarely about the damage itself; it is about whether the seller is on top of the situation. Sellers who can answer cleanly tend to hold price.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Photography, marketing, and listing presentation</h2>
      <p>Storm damage that is visible from the street or from listing photographs is a campaign problem. A blue tarp on the roof, missing tiles, a damaged carport, or fallen branches in the back yard will drop click-through rates on portal listings and discourage open home attendance. Where possible, complete temporary or cosmetic repairs before photography: a properly installed temporary roof membrane, debris removed, damaged areas screened or repaired enough to not dominate the visual story.</p>

      <p>Where damage is visible and cannot be hidden, address it directly in the listing copy and the agent's first conversation with each buyer. A short, factual line in the description ("Roof replacement in progress under insurance, scheduled for completion week of [date]; new roof warranty available to the buyer") converts a perceived negative into a piece of information. Hiding visible damage and hoping buyers do not notice is the worst strategy: it produces inspection-day surprises that reset the negotiation tone.</p>

      <p>For internal damage (water staining on ceilings, replaced internal linings, repainted areas) that has been repaired, photography can present the property normally. The disclosure pack carries the documentation. Internal damage that is current and visible needs the same direct treatment as exterior damage: address it in the description and have the documentation ready.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Pricing the damage realistically</h2>
      <p>Sellers consistently overestimate how much buyers will discount for unrepaired damage, and consistently underestimate how much buyers will discount for uncertainty. A roof replacement that the insurer is paying for and that will be completed before settlement should not produce a meaningful price discount, because the buyer is receiving a repaired property. An open hail claim with no clear resolution timeline often produces buyer offers $30,000 to $80,000 below comparable undamaged properties, even when the actual repair cost is much lower, because buyers price uncertainty into their offer.</p>

      <p>The pricing implication is that closing the claim, or at least agreeing the scope and contractor, before launching the campaign almost always produces a better net result than launching with the claim open. The market discount for "we are still talking to the insurer" is larger than the carrying cost of waiting four to eight weeks for the claim to firm up. This is one of the few decisions in selling where slowing down to prepare improves the outcome.</p>

      <p>Where the damage is genuinely small or cosmetic and the claim is not material to the property's value, a different rule applies: complete the repairs out of pocket if the insurer is slow, and sell as a fully repaired property. The repair cost is recovered (and often exceeded) by the absence of buyer uncertainty discount.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Common Brisbane scenarios</h2>
      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Hail-damaged tile or Colorbond roof, claim accepted, full replacement scheduled.</strong> Launch the campaign. Disclose openly. Time the auction or offers period to land before or shortly after roof completion so buyers can inspect a finished or near-finished property. The new roof becomes a marketing asset.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Storm water ingress through windows, internal repairs done, paint and gyprock complete.</strong> Disclose the event and the repairs. Have the building report and the painter's invoice in the contract pack. Most buyers will accept this without discount, particularly for older Brisbane homes where storm history is part of the territory.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Fallen tree caused structural damage, claim disputed on tree removal cost.</strong> Resolve the dispute before listing. A property with structural questions and an open insurer dispute is very hard to sell at a fair price. The wait is worth the certainty.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Cash-settled hail claim where seller pocketed the funds and did not repair.</strong> This is a common situation in Brisbane post-2020, post-2023, and the seller's options are: complete the repairs before listing using the cash settlement plus any top-up needed, disclose openly and price for an as-is sale, or risk a contract issue when a building inspector identifies the damage and the buyer's solicitor digs into the insurance history. Of the three, completing the repairs is almost always the right call. For more on contract structure when damage is in play, see our notes on <a href="/insights/special-conditions-queensland-property-contract-sellers" style="color:#f5d07a;">special conditions in Queensland property contracts</a> and on <a href="/insights/seller-disclosure-obligations-queensland" style="color:#f5d07a;">seller disclosure obligations in Queensland</a>.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">A practical sequencing checklist</h2>
      <p>1. Lodge or progress the insurance claim before listing. 2. Get the assessor's report and scope of works in writing. 3. Engage a contractor and confirm the schedule. 4. Decide which contract approach fits: repair before settlement, assignment of proceeds, or as-is. 5. Brief your solicitor early so the special conditions can be drafted in advance. 6. Brief your agent in detail so the disclosure conversation is consistent across every buyer interaction. 7. Prepare the documentation pack (assessor's report, scope, contractor quote, warranties, photographs) for the contract bundle. 8. Time the campaign launch to coincide with maximum claim certainty (scope agreed, contractor booked) rather than racing to market with an open question. 9. Set a price that reflects the documented position, not a worst-case discount. 10. Be ready to walk a buyer through the situation in two minutes, calmly and factually.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The bottom line</h2>
      <p>Storm and hail damage are facts of life in Brisbane property ownership. Most claims become a footnote in a successful sale, provided the seller treats the claim as a project to manage rather than a problem to hide. Documentation, a tightly drafted contract, a calm disclosure conversation with each buyer, and realistic pricing are the four levers that turn an open insurance claim from a deal risk into a non-event. Sellers who wait for the claim to fully resolve before listing get the best price; sellers who launch with the claim open, but with everything documented and a clear path to completion, can still achieve a strong result. Sellers who launch with the claim open and the documentation thin are the ones who lose money to buyer uncertainty, and those losses are larger than the cost of waiting.</p>

